Title:
Credential Guard

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post explains Microsoft Defender Credential Guard (VBS/VTL1 isolation via LsaIso.exe) and why it blocks classic LSASS credential theft, then maps publicly disclosed bypass/abuse techniques into a purple-team validation playbook.  
- It covers four attack vectors: WDigest variable patching to re-enable plaintext caching, “Pass-the-Challenge” abuse of LsaIso NTLM response functions to recover/crack NTLMv1 material, patch-downgrade to reintroduce a Credential Guard EoP (CVE-2022-34709), and SSP negotiation abuse via Remote Credential Guard/CredSSP to extract NTLMv1 responses without dumping LSASS.  
- The article references PoCs/tools (BypassCredGuard, PassTheChallenge, WindowsDowndate, DumpGuard) and notes which techniques Microsoft has mitigated (patching/downgrade) vs those still largely unresolved (pass-the-challenge, SSP negotiation).  
- It provides concrete detection guidance using Windows auditing and Sysmon (privilege adjustments, LSASS handle access, registry auditing for poqexec/CBS downgrade, Kerberos ticket events, suspicious DLL loads, and LSA API monitoring).  
- Useful for purple teams and SOC/detection engineers to test Credential Guard effectiveness beyond “LSASS dump” detections, and for red teams to understand realistic prerequisites/noise and alternative credential access paths.

Technical Focus:
- Virtualization-Based Security (VBS), Virtual Trust Levels (VTL0/VTL1), LsaIso.exe vs LSASS.exe
- WDigest internals and in-memory patching (g_IsCredGuardEnabled, g_fParameter_UseLogonCredential)
- Remote Credential Guard / CredSSP (TSSSP) and NTLMv1 response extraction
- Kerberos ticketing telemetry (TGT/TGS) and SPN/machine-account abuse
- Patch downgrade / Windows servicing (poqexec.exe, CBS/SideBySide) and CVE-2022-34709
- Detection engineering with Windows Security logs, Sysmon, and API telemetry (WriteProcessMemory, LsaCallAuthenticationPackage)

Use Cases:
- Validate Credential Guard posture and alert coverage in enterprise Windows fleets
- Simulate Credential Guard bypass attempts for purple-team exercises (PoC-driven)
- Build detections for non-LSASS-dump credential access (RCG/CredSSP/LSA package calls)
- Hunt for downgrade attempts abusing Windows servicing/poqexec registry paths
- Correlate AD events (machine account creation + Kerberos tickets) to detect SSP negotiation abuse

Keywords:
Credential Guard, VBS, VTL1, LSASS, LsaIso.exe, WDigest, g_IsCredGuardEnabled, g_fParameter_UseLogonCredential, SeDebugPrivilege, WriteProcessMemory, Pass-the-Challenge, NtlmIumCalculateNtResponse, NtlmIumLm20GetNtlm3ChallengeResponse, NTLMv1, Remote Credential Guard, CredSSP, TSSSP, LsaCallAuthenticationPackage, SPN, machine account quota, Event ID 4703, 4741, 4768, 4769, Sysmon Event ID 7, Sysmon Event ID 10, WindowsDowndate, poqexec.exe, SideBySide Configuration, CVE-2022-34709, DumpGuard, Impacket, PsExec